Hi @rpeng, do you have a concrete example that was not working as expected? I didn't see any issue with IntelliJ IDEA 2021.1.

For example, with the following:

```java
@Test
void test() {
  assertThat(new Object()).isEqualTo(0);
}
```

I get:

![Screenshot 2021-05-06 at 21 03 53](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/26772046/117351919-97d82700-aeae-11eb-9a0c-b4e59e8cf8a6.png)

which has already the link for the diff.

Hmm @scordio, I'm on IntelliJ IDEA Ultimate 2020.2, and this is what I get:


```
  @Test public void testAssert() {
    assertThat(new Object()).isEqualTo(0);
  }
```

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/575174/117355235-2b860500-ae67-11eb-9aee-de5eb4c8d3e9.png)

I wonder if IntelliJ's error parsing behavior changed between 2020.x and 2021.x versions. My initial thought was that IntelliJ's parsers were looking specifically for JUnit style assertion errors, but they may have updated it to include AssertJ's variant recently.
